<li>The EMBO Journal ( 2010 ) 29 , 1840 -- 1850  & 2010 European Molecular Biology Organization  All Rights Reserved 0261-4189/10 www.embojournal.org THE EMBO JOURNAL Two antisense RNAs target the transcriptional-regulator CsgD to inhibit curli synthesis Erik Holmqvist * , Johan Reimegård , Maaike 1 , 1 Sterk , Nina Grantcharova , Ute Römling 1 2 2 and Eduard Gerhart Heinrich Wagner * 1 , Initially , sRNAs appeared to target single genes , but multitargeting of functionally related families of mRNAs has become a recurrent theme in recent years ; this applies to , for example , E. coli and Salmonella enterica outer membrane protein ( OMP ) mRNAs targeted by RybB and OmrA/OmrB , and transporter mRNAs by GcvB ( Guillier and Gottesman , 2006 ; Vogel and Papenfort , 2006 ; Sharma et al , 2007 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two antisense RNAs target the transcriptional-regulator CsgD to inhibit curli synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23666921" target="_blank">23666921</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23378572" target="_blank">23378572</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mol Microbiol 18:661 -- 670 Holmqvist E , Reimegard J , Maaike S , Grantcharova N , Romling U , Wagner EGH ( 2010 ) Two antisense RNAs target the transcriptional-regulator CsgD to inhibit curli synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21559929" target="_blank">21559929</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_11">
Can J Microbiol 45:191 -- 200 Holmqvist E , Reimegard J , Sterk M , Grantcharova N , Römling U , Wagner EG ( 2010 ) Two antisense RNAs target the transcriptional-regulator CsgD to inhibit curli synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_11", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Holmqvist , E. , Reimegard , J. , Sterk , M. , Grantcharova , N. , Römling , U. , and Wagner , E.G. ( 2010 ) Two antisense RNAs target the transcriptional-regulator CsgD to inhibit curli synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22250746" target="_blank">22250746</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The ﬂiE and ﬂiEFGH operons for ﬂagellum formation are directly repressed by CsgD , while CsgD activates the adrA gene , which encodes an enzyme for synthesis of cyclic di-GMP , a bacterial second messenger , which in turn inhibits ﬂagellum production and rotation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides the csgBAC and csgDEFG operons , CsgD is known to regulate yaiC ( renamed to adrA ) encoding the diguanylate cyclase for the synthesis of c-di-GMP ( Chirwa and Herrington 2003 ; Pesa-vento et al. 2008 ) , which plays dual roles , enhancement of bioﬁlm formation and inhibition of cell motility through repression of ﬂagella production and rotation ( Wolfe and Visick 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23233451" target="_blank">23233451</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides the csgBAC and csgDEFG operons , CsgD is known to regulate yaiC ( renamed adrA ) , which encodes the diguanylate cyclase for the synthesis of c-di-GMP ( 14 , 38 ) and plays dual roles in the enhancement of bioﬁlm formation and inhibition of cell motility through repression of ﬂagellum production and rotation ( 52 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although CsgD has been shown to suppress glycine autotrophy and to stimulate serine hydroxymethyltransferase activity via the glyA gene ( 10 ) , little CsgD-dependent stimulation ( 1.2 - to 2-fold ) of glyA transcription was detectable when cells were grown in minimal medium supplemented with-amino-acids ( 10 ) , which is consistent with our results .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other than its effect on the rpoS regulon , CsgD expression appears to regulate a subset of anaerobiosis-dependent genes , such as ompW and pﬂB , both induced in anaerobic conditions by FNR , either alone or in concert with ArcA ( 18 , 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription activation of rpoS-dependent genes by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>These genes were chosen as representatives of known rpoS-dependent genes encoding proteins whose production is stimulated by CsgD ( dps ) , genes encoding proteins stimulated by CsgD not assigned to the rpoS regulon ( pﬂB ) , and rpoS-dependent genes encoding proteins for which no stimulation by CsgD could be detected in our SDS-PAGE experiments ( osmB ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD activation of csgB transcription in the EB1 .3 strain also indicates that the CsgD protein is fully competent in transcription activation even in an rpoS mutant , despite its localization in the inner membrane compartment ( Fig. 2B ) , which is unusual for a transcription regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to establish whether CsgD alone is sufﬁcient for csgB activation , we overexpressed the CsgD protein in an OmpR strain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to conﬁrm this possibility , we determined CsgD effects on transcription of the dps , pﬂB , and osmB genes by real-time PCR , both in the MG1655 strain and in its rpoS derivative EB1 .3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 3 , CsgD activates transcription of dps , pﬂB , and osmB genes by a similar extent ( 19 - to 30-fold ) ; however , CsgD transcription activation can only occur in the MG1655 strain , and it is totally abolished in its rpoS derivative EB1 .3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of iraP transcription in the ompR234 mutant strain was totally abolished by csgD inactivation ( Fig. 5 ) , thus conﬁrming that iraP activation observed in the PHL628 strain completely depends on CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Addition of up to 0.25 M NaCl to M9Glu/sup resulted in a less-than-twofold reduction in csgBAC transcription , which was , in contrast , totally abolished in the PHL857 strain , in which CsgD was expressed from its own promoter ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Constitutive CsgD expression promotes bioﬁlm formation by PHL565 and activates transcription from the csgBAC promoter ; however , csgBAC expression remains dependent on temperature and the growth medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to the substantial changes induced by media and temperature , the effects of growth medium osmolarity on csgBAC transcription in PHL565/pT7-CsgD were modest .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike osmolaritydependent regulation , temperature-dependent regulation of curli seems to take place at a step later than csgD transcription , as indicated by the observation that activation of csgBAC transcription by constitutively expressed CsgD is strongly inhibited at 37 ° C .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , we tested the effects of different media , as well as temperature and osmolarity ( the main environmental signals regulating curli production ) , on transcription from the csgBAC promoter in the presence of constitutively expressed CsgD protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>By expressing the CsgD protein independent of its own promoter we could determine if important environmental signals in curli regulation , such as osmolarity , temperature , and growth medium , target either the csgDEFG promoter or subsequent steps in the curli regulation cascade .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased production of the CsgD transcription activator results in activation of the csgBA operon ; when CsgD is expressed independently of OmpR , the latter becomes dispensable for activation of the csgB promoter ( Table 2 ) Both genetic and biochemical evidence shows that OmpR binds to an imperfect direct repeat ( 5 - GTTACATTTA/GTT ACATGTT-3 ) centered at position 49.5 relative to the transcriptional start site of the csgD promoter ( Table 2 and Fig. 1 and 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>These observations show that ompR234-dependent expression of csgD and activation of the csgD-dependent operons take place at very different stages in cell growth , strongly suggesting that the CsgD protein might be activated post-transcriptionally in stationary phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , although S is required for optimal transcription levels , the csgB promoter is activated by CsgD in a manner largely independent of S , strongly suggesting that S is not directly involved in protein-protein interaction between CsgD and RNA polymerase leading to transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>ompR234-independent CsgD expression resulted in activation of the csgB promoter , and in repression of pepD and yagS expression ( data not shown ) , strongly suggesting that these genes are indeed directly controlled by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overexpression of CsgD resulted in stimulation of csgBA expression , suggesting that OmpR is required for activation of the csgD but not the csgBA promoter ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 5 , CsgD can increase transcription levels of the iraP gene by 15-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , CsgD activation of the iraP gene should result in improved S stability and possibly increase S intracellular concentrations , resulting in increased transcription of S-depen-dent genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>We report here that CsgD transcription activation of the iraP gene does indeed result in a signiﬁcant increase of S intracellular concentratio by positively affecting S protein stability ( Fig. 6 and 7 ) , thus leading to altered expression of S-dependent genes ( Fig. 2 , 3 , 4B , and 6B and Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased csgD transcription was exclusively due to the presence of the pT7-CsgD expression vector and was independent of the csgDEFG promoter , as indicated by a lack of any increase in csgEFG transcripts ( see the results for real-time PCR experiments ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Either way , an increase in the cellular S pool in conditions permitting csg gene expression ( i.e. , low osmolarity ) leads to increased transcription from the csgD promoter ; in turn , production of the CsgD protein results in iraP activation and consequent further stabilization of S. Evidence for this auto-regulatory mechanism in the MG1655 strain is provided by S-dependent activation of the csgD promoter in the presence of pT7CsgD ( Fig. 4B ) and by consequent production of proteins encoded by the csgDEFG operon , such as CsgG ( Fig. 2C ) , in response to CsgD-dependent accumulation of S. Indeed , S-dependent activation of the csgDEFG operon observed in Fig. 4B is impaired in an iraP mutant strain ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike the levels of transcription of the csgBAC operon , the levels of transcription of the csgE , csgF and csgG genes ( i.e. , the csgDEFG operon ) were not altered by the presence of the pT7-CsgD plasmid , strongly suggesting that the CsgD protein does not regulate its own gene and indicating that , despite the presence of a functional chromosomal copy of csgD in the PHL565/pT7-CsgD strain , csgD expression is solely dependent on the plasmid copy of the gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to evaluate the specific effects of CsgD overexpression , we compared MG1655/pT7CsgD to MG1655 transformed with the pT7-7 vector .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with their being part of the rpoS regulon , no CsgD-dependent increase in protein expression of GadA , WrbA , Dps , and CsgG could be detected in EB1 .3 / pT7CsgD , an rpoS mutant of MG1655 transformed with the pT7CsgD plasmid ( Fig. 2 , lanes 4 and 10 ) , thus suggesting that regulation by CsgD does not bypass the need for S .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with the lack of CsgD-dependent increase in S intracellular concentration in LG03 ( iraP mutant ; Fig. 6A , lane 4 ) , the CsgD protein failed to stimulate expression of the GadA , WrbA and Dps proteins in this strain ( Fig. 6B , lane 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>To conﬁrm that CsgD-dependent accumulation of S is indeed mediated by S stabilization via the IraP protein , we performed S protein turnover assays in cell extracts of either MG1655 or its iraP mutant derivative ( LG03 ) , grown both in the presence or in the absence of the pT7CsgD plasmid .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 7 , the stability of the S protein is increased in cell extracts of MG1655/pT7CsgD compared to MG1655 / pT7-7 ; however , no CsgD-dependent S stabilization could be detected in cell extracts of the LG03/pT7CsgD strain , a ﬁnding consistent with a direct role of the IraP protein in CsgDmediated stabilization of S .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 2A , CsgD expression from the pT7-CsgD plasmid resulted in a fourfold increase in surface attachment by the PHL565 strain in M9Glu/sup and in a roughly twofold increase in LB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased Congo red binding and surface colonization induced by pT7-CsgD were indeed dependent on curli , since transformation with pT7-CsgD of the PHL856 strain , a PHL565 de-rivative in which the csgA gene encoding the main curli subunit has been inactivated , did not result in surface attachment ( Fig. 2A ) or in Congo red binding ( Fig. 2B ) by this strain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among the proteins negatively regulated by CsgD , we could identify band 5 as a mixture of TnaA ( tryptophanase [ 22 ] ) and GatZ ( involved in galactitol catabolism ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the pepD gene appeared to be 4-fold negatively regulated by CsgD in real-time PCR experiments , similar to the 4-fold repression observed for the curli-express-ing PHL628 derivative of PHL565 ( 7 ) and to the 2.5-fold repression observed for the PHL565/pT7-CsgD gene array compared with the PHL565/pT7 -7 gene array ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , expression of the OmpW protein ( band 10 ) , although stimulated by CsgD , appears to be negatively regulated by S ( Fig. 2 , compare lanes 11 and 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to fecR and cspA , the yoaD gene is activated by the CsgD protein ( Table 3 ) , although it also negatively affects cell aggregation ( Fig. 5A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Likewise , the fepDGC operon , encoding iron-enterobactin transporters , was predicted to be regulated by CsgD ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>The gatY gene , together with gatZ , is part of the gatZYABC operon ( 42 ) , which , as we already showed , is negatively regulated by CsgD ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the gatZYABC operon , negatively controlled by CsgD ( 10 ) ( Table 2 ) is repressed by ArcA in anaerobic conditions ( 60 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>If this is the case , the set of genes under the control of the CsgD global regulator must be activated in the presence of MlrA overexpression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20874755" target="_blank">20874755</a>]<br></li>
<li>If yaiC is regulated by CsgD , one would predict that yaiC should also be under positive control by YdaM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptome analysis in the presence of overexpressed CsgD indicated that the iron-sensing proteins FecR and FhuE are under the control of CsgD ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of iron-sensing genes , such as fecR and fhuE , in the CsgD regulon might allow modulation of the intracellular iron concentration during the transition from planktonic cells to attached cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>After transfer of proteins onto ﬁlters , the protein-blotted ﬁlter was treated with anti-CsgD antibody , which was raised in rabbits against puriﬁed CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>After induction of CsgD expression by adding arabinose , cells were treated with formaldehyde for protein-DNA cross-linking .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>They also dem-onstrated that CsgD could be phosphorylated in vitro using acetyl phosphate and this reduced the binding of the protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>To conﬁrm that the genes carrying the putative binding site for CsgD are indeed regulated by this protein , and not by OmpR234 , we performed quantitative PCR experiments in strains expressing the CsgD protein independently of the ompR234 allele .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unfortunately , we have failed to obtain any active CsgD protein thus far .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of the conserved sequence suggests that both pepD and yagS might be directly regulated by the CsgD protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>PHL565/pT7-CsgD are indeed directly regulated by the CsgD protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>The only major difference observed in the inner membrane compartment was the presence of a rather large band of ca. 25 kDa in EB1 .3 / pT7CsgD , identiﬁed as the CsgD protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lanes 1 , 3 , and 5 , PHL565/pT7 -7 ; lanes 2 , 4 , and 6 , PHL565/pT7-CsgD ; lanes 1 and 2 , cytoplasmic proteins ( C ) ; lanes 3 and 4 , inner membrane proteins ( IM ) ; lanes 5 and 6 , outer membrane proteins ( OM ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both CsgD3 and CsgD1 were equally active in CsgD binding , but the CsgD2 segment showed weak but signiﬁcant CsgD binding activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because CsgD most probably is a transcriptional-regulator it could conceivably induce production of potential Congo red binding proteins other than those encoded by the csg operons .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8817489" target="_blank">8817489</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of CsgD on bioﬁlm development on polystyrene microtiter plates and Congo red binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>It should be noted , however , that the functional form of CsgD remains unidentiﬁed under the culture conditions employed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , it can not be ruled out that there were two forms of CsgD , i.e. , phosphorylated and unphosphoryl-ated , under the experimental conditions employed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , CsgD activates ihfB , known to repress FlhD ( 2 , 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>For instance , CsgD is supposed to be phosphorylated through an as-yet-unidentiﬁed mechanism ( 56 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the proposed model ( Fig. 6C ) , the regulatory path CpxR-OmpR-CsgD-FliA could explain the observed repressive effects of CpxR on ﬂiA transcription and cell motility ; another route , independent of CsgD ( CpxR-OmpR-FlhDC-FliA ) , also explains the negative regulation of ﬂiA by CpxR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>A key functional interaction in the model proposed in Fig. 6C is the repression of ﬂiA by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistently , overexpression of BluF resulted in decreased levels of CsgD ( Fig. 3D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22783906" target="_blank">22783906</a>]<br></li>
<li>S1c , Online Resource ) to determine if the presence of normal levels of CsgD in the cell affected expression ( Fig. 4a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to elucidate the mechanism by which CsgD and CpxR repress cell motility , we measured the expression kinetics of ﬂiA , ﬂgM , and tar in the corresponding mutant strains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD and CpxR regulate motility through several known regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION CsgD and CpxR regulate motility and adhesion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD and CpxR repress ﬂagellar biosynthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>( C ) Known functions and interactions between RpoS , CsgD , and CpxR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results conﬁrm that CsgD and CpxR repress cell motility without affecting RpoS activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since direct repression by a sigma factor is a rare mechanism , we screened for potential transcriptional-repressors activated by RpoS and found two regulators , CsgD and CpxR , both of which repress cell motility .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIG 4 Repression of ﬂagellar class 2 and 3 genes by RpoS , CsgD , and CpxR in M9 minimal medium ( A to C ) or LB medium ( D to F ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>) Negative regulation of cell motility by RpoS is likely mediated by direct binding of CsgD to the promoter of ﬂagellar class 2 genes ( ﬂiE , ﬂiF , ﬂiA , and ﬂgM ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data suggest that they regulate distinct targets of the network controlling ﬂagellar biosynthesis and that CsgD directly represses the ﬂiA and ﬂgM promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD directly represses transcription of both the ﬂiE and ﬂiFGHIJK operons by binding to the spacer region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we found that CpxR represses ﬂiA more strongly than RpoS or CsgD ( Fig. 4A and D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD represses the transcription of dksA , itself known to repress the transcription of ﬂhD and ﬂiA following starvation ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we demonstrate that CsgD represses part of the ﬂagellar regulatory cascade through speciﬁc inhibition of ﬂiA transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected , the intensity of unbound DNA decreases proportionally to the increase of CsgD concentration in the assay for each promoter but not for the lacZ promoter DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD binds to the ﬂgM and ﬂiA pro- moters around their 10 promoter element , strongly suggesting direct repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>This in vitro experiment also suggests a direct repression of the ﬂgM promoter by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>In good agreement with the location of the CsgD-binding site , the ﬂiE promoter activity markedly increased in the csgD mutant ( Fig. 9A ) , indicating repression of ﬂiE by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the apparent repression of the ﬂiF promoter by CsgD may also be attributable to interference of FlhDC in binding to its target site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>After a promoter-lacZ fusion assay , the CsgD targets were classiﬁed into two groups : group I genes , such as ﬂiE and yhbT , are repressed by CsgD , while group II genes , including yccT and adrA , are activated by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>A group of promoters were activated in the csgD mutant , indicating that CsgD is involved as a repressor for this group of promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effects of CsgD on the ﬂiE and ﬂiF promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>These interactions are consistent with known properties of CsgD and the idea of a direct repression of these regulatory genes by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among the up-regulated genes we found , as expected , csgBAC and adrA , which are known to be CsgD regulated , and csgD itself .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcription of rprA is activated by the Rcs phosphorelay system OxyS ArcZ S σ RprA DsrA CsgD McaS GcvB OmpR OmrA OmrB Fig. 9 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22250746" target="_blank">22250746</a>]<br></li>
<li>The present ﬁnding that CsgD synthesis is negatively controlled by the glycine induced GcvB RNA further indicates that sensing glycine levels and adjusting glycine synthesis via GcvB are an integral part of the CsgD regulatory network .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22250746" target="_blank">22250746</a>]<br></li>
<li>This repressor effect on csgBA synthesis was dominant following activation by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16000739" target="_blank">16000739</a>]<br></li>
<li>Its destabili-zation increases CsgD synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>This raises the important question when and under which conditions sRNA regulation of CsgD synthesis occurs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>We infer that both direct inhibition of CsgD synthesis , and inhibition of csgD transcription through inhibition of ompR , contribute to the total regulation observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>OmrA/B inhibition of CsgD synthesis seems to be yet another case of ` upstream ' regulation , although the available data do not appear to ﬁt any of the above models .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>OmrA/B downregulate plasmidborne csgD-gfp fusions in vivo , and inhibit CsgD translation in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>The in vivo and vitro results thus conﬁrm that binding of the sRNA to its target mRNA is direct and entails inhibition of CsgD synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of Hfq , OmrB efﬁciently inhibited CsgD synthesis even at the lowest concentration ; in absence of Hfq , inhibition was quite ineffective ( Figure 5C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Preliminary experiments using a chromosomal csgD-3xFLAG gene carrying the M4 mutation ( Figure 3 ) indicates that most of the inhibition of CsgD synthesis is due to direct targeting of csgD rather than through OmpR ; csgD mRNA levels were decreased to E50 % in the presence of OmrA-wt ( which matches the ompR but not csgD-M4 target ) , but to E90 % by OmrA-M4 ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the tol mutants , activation of csgDEFG occurred via OmpR and was dominant upon repression by RcsB and RcsA , while these two regulatory proteins repressed csgBA through a dominant effect on the activator protein CsgD , thus affecting curli synthesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16000739" target="_blank">16000739</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under such conditions , the activation of csgDEFG probably occurs via OmpR , which is dominant upon repression by RcsAB , while RcsB and RcsA could repress csgAB through a dominant negative effect on CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16000739" target="_blank">16000739</a>]<br></li>
<li>The time-varying concentration of IHF could thus modulate CsgD accumulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given these data , an attractive hypothesis is that CsgD could be the missing factor necessary for transcriptional activation by Crl in the purified systems .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14978043" target="_blank">14978043</a>]<br></li>
