<li>Moreover , to monitor CsgD synthesis and to stabilize the message the very end of the csgD gene was equipped with a sequence encoding a triple FLAG epitope followed by the rho-independent terminator sequence of the ompA gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22250746" target="_blank">22250746</a>]<br></li>
<li>CpxR , CsgD , CRP , RstA , OmpR and Cra-binding sites are indicated csgB coding sequence TTGTTTTTCATGTTGTCACCCTGGACCTGGTCGTACATTTAAGAAATTAAATCATTTCAACTTGGTTGT TAACGCAACCTGTATTTTGTTAACGCTGCGTTACGATGGAAAGTATGTCTGCGGAAATATTTTTAATAA csgBp CTCACCCGCGCGTTGTATTTTTCTTTTTTAGTTCATACCAAAGTATTAAAACCCACGTAAATACGCTGT TATCTACGCAAAAAAATATTTTGTTTTCTTTTAAATCTCCGTTTTCCGCTATCAAAAAGCACCAGACAG TCATTCTTCTTGCCCGTCGCTGATTGCTGCGATATGTCTTGCGCACAAGCCGTGACAAACCTCGTCTTT TTGCAGTAAAAAATTGTCCACGGAGGTGTGGAGAAAAAACAAGAACGTTTTACATGACGAAAGGACTAC ACCGAAATATTTTTTATATGCATTATTAGTAAGTTATCACCATTTGTATGATTTTTTAAAATTGTGCAA TAAAAACCAAATGTACAACTTTTCTATCATTTCTAAACTTAATAAAACCTTAAGGTTAACATTTTAATA csgDp1 TAACGAGTTACATTTAGTTACATGTTTAACACTTGATTTAAGATTTGTAATGGCTAGATTGAAATCAGA csgDp2 TGTAATCCATTAGTTTTATATTTTACCCATTTAGGGCTGATTTATTACTACACACAGCAGTGCAACATC TGTCAGTACTTCTGGTGCTTCTATTTTAGAGGCAGCTGTCAGGTGTGCGATCAATAAAAAAAGCGGGGT csgD coding sequence TTCATCATGTTTAATGAAGTCCATAGTAT RstA-P CpxR-P CpxR-P CpxR-P csgDp1 OmpR csgDp2 Cra Cra CRP-AMP CRP-AMP CpxR-P CpxR-P Cra CpxR-P Cra CsgD csgBp J. Altenbuchner and S. E. Lindow , respectively , while bacteriophage P1vir was a kind gift from S. K. Apte .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21559929" target="_blank">21559929</a>]<br></li>
<li>Individual DNA binding sites recognized by CsgD are labelled D1 to D4 , which refers to speciﬁc positions within the target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two recent studies have identified binding sites for CsgD in E. coli ( Ogasawara et al. 2011 ) and S. enterica servovar typhimurium ( Zakikhany et al. 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased production of the CsgD transcription activator results in activation of the csgBA operon ; when CsgD is expressed independently of OmpR , the latter becomes dispensable for activation of the csgB promoter ( Table 2 ) Both genetic and biochemical evidence shows that OmpR binds to an imperfect direct repeat ( 5 - GTTACATTTA/GTT ACATGTT-3 ) centered at position 49.5 relative to the transcriptional start site of the csgD promoter ( Table 2 and Fig. 1 and 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>Noteworthy is that the eight members of the CsgD regulon so far identiﬁed in this study carry one to four CsgD-binding sequences that are located at various positions from the respective transcription start position ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our experiments conﬁrmed the already reported transcription start site for csgB ( Arnqvist et al. , 1994 ) ; the conserved sequence necessary for activation by CsgD overlaps the 235 region ( from 242 to 232 ; Fig. 3b ) , consistent with the location for an activator binding site ( Busby & Ebright , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conservation of this 11 bp sequence in both csgB and yaiC points to a possible regulatory role ; indeed , substitutions in this sequence [ to either ATTCCATTAGG ( PmutcsgB1 ) or ATTCCATTTTA ( PmutcsgB2 ) in the csgB and to ATTCCATTAGG ( PmutyaiC1 ) in the yaiC promoters ] result in total loss of activation by CsgD ( Fig. 2b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Brombacher et al. ( 55 ) have recently identified an 11-bp sequence ( CGGGKGAKNKA ) located upstream of the csgBA promoter elements ( from 42 to 32 ) that is necessary for the transcriptional activation by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14978043" target="_blank">14978043</a>]<br></li>
<li>The promoter regions of these four genes share a conserved 11 bp sequence ( CGGGKGAKNKA ) , necessary for csgBA and yaiC regulation by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both csgB and yaiC require an 11 bp conserved sequence for activation by CsgD ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>While at both the csgBA and yaiC promoters the sequence is located upstream of the promoter elements , in both yagS and pepD it overlaps either the putative '' 10 sequence or the transcription start point , suggesting that CsgD can function as both an activator and a repressor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , according to our results , the start point for pepD2 would be located within the conserved 11 bp sequence , consistent with a possible role of CsgD as a repressor at the pepD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding site is present as an inverted-repeat in the yaiC promoter region , possibly suggesting that CsgD might bind this promoter as a dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD directly binds the 10 promoter element of ﬂiA and ﬂgM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>( B ) Consensus sequence for CsgD binding and sequences of the binding sites found around the 10 promoter element of the csgD , ﬂiA , and ﬂgM promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>From our results , we can not establish whether CsgD activates iraP expression via direct interaction with the iraP promoter or through additional factors : we could not ﬁnd in the iraP promoter region any sequence closely resembling the putative binding site for CsgD identiﬁed in the CsgD-dependent csgB , adrA , and pepD promoters ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>To demonstrate speciﬁc binding of CsgD to these promoters , we added a competitor DNA , the lacZ promoter that does not contain a sequence similar to that of the CsgD binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>To conﬁrm that the sequence we identiﬁed indeed serves as a CsgD-binding site , we attempted to purify the CsgD protein for in vitro studies .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>The conserved sequence ( CGGGKGAKNKA ) is totally unrelated to any so far reported OmpR-binding sites , and we propose that it might be the target sequence for CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequences of these promoter segments were analyzed to identify the consensus sequence of the CsgD box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consensus sequence of the CsgD box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>knowledge of the CsgD recognition sequence on the two promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Identiﬁcation of the CsgD recognition sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Examination of these sequences reveals conserved A or C nucleotides at positions 11 and 12 ( Fig. 5B ) , leading to an updated version of the consensus sequence for CsgD binding , AAAAGNGNNAMMWW .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 5B presents the consensus sequence for CsgD binding ( AAAAGNGNNAAAWW [ 38 ] ) and the potential binding site overlapping the 10 promoter elements of the ﬂagellar regulatory genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>The two CsgD binding motifs present on the ﬂgM promoter have more mismatches to the proposed consensus sequence for CsgD binding than the unique , high-afﬁnity site found at the ﬂiA promoter ( Fig. 5B and C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>( The underlined nucleotides correspond to two modiﬁcations of the consensus sequence for CsgD binding which was previously proposed as AAAAGNGNNAAAWW in reference 38 and as shown in Fig. 5B .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
				</ul></div><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by CsgD</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>Removal of the 50-most 66 nucleotides ( pCsgD : : GFP ; Figure 7B ) from the 83 E. coli sequence did not signiﬁcantly change csgD : : gfp expression or control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20407422" target="_blank">20407422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression levels of the iraP genes , normalized to 16S rRNA , are shown as relative values in MG1655/pT7CsgD in comparison to MG1655/pT7 -7 , as well as in PHL628 ( ompR234 ) and PHL1087 ( ompR234 csgD : : kan ) in comparison to MG1655 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of these operons is positively regulated by OmpR ( via the activation of CsgD ) ( Romling et al. , 1998 ) , and negatively regulated by CpxR ( Dorel et al. , 1999 ; Otto & Silhavy , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16000739" target="_blank">16000739</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under such conditions , the activation of csgDEFG probably occurs via OmpR , which is dominant upon repression by RcsAB , while RcsB and RcsA could repress csgAB through a dominant negative effect on CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16000739" target="_blank">16000739</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬂiE and ﬂiEFGH operons for ﬂagellum formation are directly repressed by CsgD , while CsgD activates the adrA gene , which encodes an enzyme for synthesis of cyclic di-GMP , a bacterial second messenger , which in turn inhibits ﬂagellum production and rotation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides the csgBAC and csgDEFG operons , CsgD is known to regulate yaiC ( renamed to adrA ) encoding the diguanylate cyclase for the synthesis of c-di-GMP ( Chirwa and Herrington 2003 ; Pesa-vento et al. 2008 ) , which plays dual roles , enhancement of bioﬁlm formation and inhibition of cell motility through repression of ﬂagella production and rotation ( Wolfe and Visick 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23233451" target="_blank">23233451</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides the csgBAC and csgDEFG operons , CsgD is known to regulate yaiC ( renamed adrA ) , which encodes the diguanylate cyclase for the synthesis of c-di-GMP ( 14 , 38 ) and plays dual roles in the enhancement of bioﬁlm formation and inhibition of cell motility through repression of ﬂagellum production and rotation ( 52 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , csgBA operon transcription levels at 30 uC and 37 uC are comparable in MG1655 / pT7CsgD ( Table 3 ) , suggesting that increased biofilm formation at 37 uC in this strain is not mediated by a corresponding increase in curli production .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , autoregulation of the csgDEFG operon by CsgD u appears to still take place at 37 C , although overall u csgDEFG transcription levels are much lower at 37 C than u at 30 C even in MG1655/pT7CsgD ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>In plasmid pT7CsgD , the csgD gene is under the control of a T7 RNA polymerase-dependent promoter , which is only weakly recognized by E. coli RNA polymerase ( Brown & Campbell , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>For csgD expression , the csgD gene was cloned from the pCP900 plasmid ( 42 ) into the pT7-7 plasmid using the NdeI and PstI sites to obtain the pT7-CsgD plasmid , in which csgD was under the control of a phage T7 RNA polymerase-dependent promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>For instance , CsgD induces the expression of iraP , which encodes a stabilization factor of the RpoS sigma factor , by interfering with the RssB-mediated proteolysis of RpoS by the ClpXP protease ( Bougdour & Gottesman , 2007 ; Gualdi et al. , 2007 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20466769" target="_blank">20466769</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to conﬁrm this possibility , we determined CsgD effects on transcription of the dps , pﬂB , and osmB genes by real-time PCR , both in the MG1655 strain and in its rpoS derivative EB1 .3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 3 , CsgD activates transcription of dps , pﬂB , and osmB genes by a similar extent ( 19 - to 30-fold ) ; however , CsgD transcription activation can only occur in the MG1655 strain , and it is totally abolished in its rpoS derivative EB1 .3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>These genes were chosen as representatives of known rpoS-dependent genes encoding proteins whose production is stimulated by CsgD ( dps ) , genes encoding proteins stimulated by CsgD not assigned to the rpoS regulon ( pﬂB ) , and rpoS-dependent genes encoding proteins for which no stimulation by CsgD could be detected in our SDS-PAGE experiments ( osmB ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other than its effect on the rpoS regulon , CsgD expression appears to regulate a subset of anaerobiosis-dependent genes , such as ompW and pﬂB , both induced in anaerobic conditions by FNR , either alone or in concert with ArcA ( 18 , 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription from the csgBA promoter requires CsgD Extracts , boiled in SDS , of mutants with insertions in each of the csgDEFG genes were also probed with the CsgA-specific polyclonal antiserum by Western blotting .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8817489" target="_blank">8817489</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the yfgG and ygcI operons could be regulation targets of CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Except for the csgDEFG and csgBAC operons , the participation of CsgD in transcription regulation has not been identiﬁed for the other six operons , ﬂiE ( encoding the ﬂagellum basal body protein ) , ﬂiFGHIJK ( encoding ﬂagellum components and assembly proteins ) , yccT , yccU , wrbA-yccJ , and ymdF .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD directly represses transcription of both the ﬂiE and ﬂiFGHIJK operons by binding to the spacer region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since CsgD is required for csgBA transcription and is produced in an hns rpoS double mutant it may be that this protein has the capability to respond to starvation and/or high cell density by activating csgBA transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8817489" target="_blank">8817489</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD represses the transcription of dksA , itself known to repress the transcription of ﬂhD and ﬂiA following starvation ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>While McaS represses synthesis of one transcription factor , CsgD , it increases synthesis of another transcription factor , FlhD and also likely the FlhC transcription factor encoded on the same transcript .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22289118" target="_blank">22289118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of the conserved sequence suggests that both pepD and yagS might be directly regulated by the CsgD protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>By expressing the CsgD protein independent of its own promoter we could determine if important environmental signals in curli regulation , such as osmolarity , temperature , and growth medium , target either the csgDEFG promoter or subsequent steps in the curli regulation cascade .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to the substantial changes induced by media and temperature , the effects of growth medium osmolarity on csgBAC transcription in PHL565/pT7-CsgD were modest .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Addition of up to 0.25 M NaCl to M9Glu/sup resulted in a less-than-twofold reduction in csgBAC transcription , which was , in contrast , totally abolished in the PHL857 strain , in which CsgD was expressed from its own promoter ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , three of the main cold shock-induced genes in E. coli ( cspA , cspB , and cspG ) ( 29 , 54 ) appeared to be down-regulated by factors of four - to sevenfold in PHL565/pT7-CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>The two genes are cotranscribed in the fecIR operon ( 41 , 49 ) , and the level of the fecI transcript is 2.5-fold lower in PHL565 / pT7-CsgD ( data not shown ) , which is consistent with the possibility that there is either direct or indirect transcriptional repression of the whole fecIR operon by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>For these genes , the real-time PCR results closely reﬂected the results of the whole-genome transcription assays , showing that there was an eightfold increase for the yoaD transcript and a roughly fourfold decrease for both the cspA and fecR transcripts in PHL565/pT7-CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the gatY , gatB , gatD , and gatR genes are not listed in Table 3 , they were all downregulated in PHL565/pT7-CsgD by factors ranging from 2.7 - to 3.3-fold , suggesting that the whole gat transcription unit is indeed repressed in a CsgD-dependent fashion ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our assays showed that there was 4.5-fold repression of transcription of both the fecR and fhuE genes in PHL565/pT7-CsgD ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results of whole-genome transcription assay and real-time PCR Mean whole-genome transcription pT7-CsgD/pT7 -7 ratio ( SD ) Mean realtime PCR Gene Function of gene product pT7-CsgD/pT7 -7 ratio ( SD ) Up-regulated genes in PHL565/pT7-CsgD compared to PHL565/pT7 -7 adrA ( yaiC ) csgB csgA csgC csgD gsk yaiB yjgW ymdA yoaD ytfI Down-regulated genes in PHL565/pT7-CsgD compared to PHL565/pT7 -7 cspA cspB cspG fecR fhuE gatA gatC gatZ infA metA ompF ompT pyrB pyrI Genes belonging to the csgDEFG operon or previously described as CsgD dependent csgE csgF csgG glyA pepD a ND , not determined .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , we tested genes belonging to the csgBAC and csgDEFG operons and genes proposed to be CsgD dependent ( adrA , glyA , and pepD ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two genes encoding outer membrane proteins , the main OmpF porin and the OmpT protease , as well as the methionine biosynthesis metA gene , were also down-regulated in PHL565/pT7-CsgD ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of the glyA gene was only weakly stimulated ( 1.3-fold ) by the CsgD protein according to the results of our real-time experiments ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among the novel identiﬁed genes whose expression was affected by CsgD , we tested the EAL protein-encoding yoaD gene , as well as the fecR and cspA genes , in real-time PCR experiments ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to adrA and yoaD , a third GMP-related gene , gsk , was found to be more highly expressed in PHL565/pT7-CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased Congo red binding and surface colonization induced by pT7-CsgD were indeed dependent on curli , since transformation with pT7-CsgD of the PHL856 strain , a PHL565 de-rivative in which the csgA gene encoding the main curli subunit has been inactivated , did not result in surface attachment ( Fig. 2A ) or in Congo red binding ( Fig. 2B ) by this strain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription from the csgBAC promoter was determined in the PHL856 strain transformed with either pT7-7 or pT7-CsgD ; in PHL856 the csgA gene is interrupted by a uidA gene encoding - glucuronidase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Likewise , the fepDGC operon , encoding iron-enterobactin transporters , was predicted to be regulated by CsgD ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of csgBAC is positively regulated by CsgD , which is part of the csgDEFG operon and is divergently transcribed from the intergenic region between it and the csgBAC locus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21415116" target="_blank">21415116</a>]<br></li>
<li>In parallel , we also examined the possible inﬂuence of CsgD on the promoter of the ﬂiF operon , which is transcribed in a different direction from the ﬂiE gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>The gatY gene , together with gatZ , is part of the gatZYABC operon ( 42 ) , which , as we already showed , is negatively regulated by CsgD ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the gatZYABC operon , negatively controlled by CsgD ( 10 ) ( Table 2 ) is repressed by ArcA in anaerobic conditions ( 60 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus it is proposed that CsgD stimulates bioﬁlm formation in E. coli by contemporary activation of Received 18 February 2003 Revised 26 May 2003 adhesion positive determinants ( the curli-encoding csg operons and the product of the yaiC gene ) and repression of negative effectors such as yagS and pepD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our ﬁnding that the ydaM and yciR mutations affect the expression of csg genes only , also raises the question why some other genes that are believed to be under the control of CsgD ( Brombacher et al. , 2003 ; 2006 ) , are not differentially expressed in these mutants .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>FlhD2C2 activates expression of a cascade of ~ 50 genes involved in motility and chemotaxis , including fliE and fliFGHIJK , two operons known to be repressed by CsgD , and yhjI , a gene encoding a phosphodiesterase that modulates c-di-GMP levels ( Soutourina & Bertin , 2003 , Ogasawara et al. , 2011 , Pesavento et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22289118" target="_blank">22289118</a>]<br></li>
<li>The csgC gene is expressed in response to CsgD ( Brombacher et al. 2006 ; Weber et al. 2006 ) , but its function is not known .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of the bcsA gene was not affected by CsgD overexpression ( data not shown ) , suggesting that expression of the bcs operon is independent of CsgD , as previously reported for Salmonella ( Romling et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>The FixJ/LuxR family protein CsgD is a key regulator for curli production , and modulates the expression of not only the csg operon encoding components and assembly of curli ( Hammar et al. 1995 ) , but also a set of genes for adaptation of cell physiology to the bioﬁlm lifestyle ( Chirwa and Herrington 2003 ; Brombacher et al. 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23233451" target="_blank">23233451</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of the curli operons is under the control of the CsgD protein , the first gene product of the csgDEFG operon ( Hammar et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20466769" target="_blank">20466769</a>]<br></li>
<li>A GGDEF cascade : YdaM controls the expression of YaiC The CsgD regulatory protein is known to control at least one more gene besides the csgBAC curli structural operon : in Salmonella this gene is called adrA ( Römling et al. , 2000 ) , in E. coli it is yaiC ( Brombacher et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides the previously described ydaM , yciR , yegE and yhjH genes , these are yhdA ( csrD ) , which stimulates the expression of the DGC YdaM and the major curli regulator CsgD , and yeaP , which contributes to expression of the curli structural operon csgBAC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19332833" target="_blank">19332833</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of the csgBAC operon , which encodes the curli structural proteins , is driven by a regulatory cascade consisting of sS , the MerR-like regulator MlrA and the CsgD regulatory protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>Curli-encoding genes are clustered in two operons : csgBA encodes the structural components , while the divergently oriented csgDEFG operon encodes proteins involved in curli assembly and transport ( 38 ) , as well as the CsgD transcription factor , which is necessary for csgBA transcription ( 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The genes for curli synthesis are clustered in two divergent operons ; the csgBA operon encodes the structural components of curli and the csgDEFG operon encodes a positive regulator of curli synthesis ( CsgD ) as well as proteins required for curli secretion and assembly ( Römling et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22250746" target="_blank">22250746</a>]<br></li>
<li>The csgD gene encodes the transcription regulator CsgD , which in turn activates transcription of the csgBA operon encoding curli , extracellular structures involved in bacterial adhesion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of both curli and cellulose depends on the CsgD protein , a putative transcription regulator of the LuxR family , which activates transcription of the csgBAC operon ( 2 ) , which encodes curli structural subunits , and transcription of the adrA gene , a positive effector of cellulose biosynthesis ( 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of the csgBA operon is fairly complex and involves the transcription activator CsgD , the product of the ﬁrst gene in the csgDEFG operon ( 3 , 44 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CsgG protein is a component of the curli transport system and is encoded by a gene belonging to the csgDEFG operon , which also encodes CsgD ( 28 , 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬁrst gene of the csgDEFG operon encodes the CsgD protein , a putative transcription factor belonging to the luxR family and required for the transcription of csgBA ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>To better understand the mechanism of temperature regulation of both curli - and cellulose-related genes , we performed gene expression experiments on the cellulose-related bcsA ( cellulose biosynthesis ) and adrA ( regulator of cellulose production ) genes , as well as on the csgG and csgB genes , which were chosen as representative of the two operons involved in curli biosynthesis ( csgDEFG and csgBA ) , and on the csgD gene , to estimate the extent of its overexpression in MG1655 / pT7CsgD ( Table 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>At 30 uC , CsgD overexpression from pT7CsgD results in increased transcription of both the curli-encoding csgBA operon and the adrA gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that , when expressed at 37 uC , CsgD would activate transcription of the curli-encoding csgBA operon , but not of the cellulose biosynthetic adrA and bcs genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that CsgD overexpression can overcome temperature-dependent control of the curli-encoding csgBA operon , but not of the cellulose-related adrA gene , suggesting very tight temperature control of cellulose production in E. coli MG1655 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , in contrast to the curli-related csg operons , the adrA gene , encoding a diguanylate cyclase regulating cellulose production , is not activated by constitutive expression of CsgD at 37 uC ( Table 3 ) , thus suggesting tighter temperature-dependent control of its transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>This complex feedforward arrangement , which converges in csgD expression ( the downstream target csgBAC is expressed from a vegetative promoter activated by CsgD ) probably not only increases the amplitude and precision of induction of the downstream target ( feedforward loops can ﬁlter out sto-chastic noise in gene expression ; Mangan and Alon , 2003 ) , but also restricts target expression to very speciﬁc conditions by allowing additional signal integration in the indirectly operating cascade part ( s ) of the feedforward system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>The csgB promoter is transcribed by vegetative polymerase and indirectly sS-activated via CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>Most modulators of E. coli cell motility are regulated by RpoS , CsgD , or CpxR both in exponential phase ( data not shown ) and in stationary phase ( Fig. 6B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed we observed that during entry into stationary phase , i.e. when CsgD and curli ﬁmbriae are expressed in the wild type , the expression of ydaM is reduced in the hns mutant ( Fig. 8C ) , whereas yciR expression is stimulated ( Fig. 8D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to elucidate the mechanism by which CsgD and CpxR repress cell motility , we measured the expression kinetics of ﬂiA , ﬂgM , and tar in the corresponding mutant strains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of CsgD expression , the S half-life in cell extracts of the iraP mutant is similar to MG1655 ( 14 versus 12 min , respectively ) , as detected by image analysis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>We observed a small induction of the hmp gene ( adjacent to glyA ) by ectopically expressed CsgD ( Chirwa and Herrington 2004 ) and so we tested it as well .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>We observed a small increase in hmp expression when CsgD was expressed from a plasmid ( Chirwa and Herrington 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with our observation that a chimeric protein lacking the presumptive DNA-binding HTH motif of CsgD also induced glyA expression ( Chirwa and Herrington 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , CsgD has been shown to activate expression of the glyA gene , encoding serine hydroxymethyltransferase , through an unknown mechanism ( Chirwa and Herrington , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22250746" target="_blank">22250746</a>]<br></li>
<li>At late times of growth , expression of genes responsible for methylene tetrahydrofolate synthesis ( glyA and gcvTHP ) and formyltetrahydrofolate recycling ( purU ) was higher in cells with CsgD than those without .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>This notion is supported by the observation that the newly identiﬁed csgD-regulated genes yoaD ( up-regulated by CsgD ) , fecR , and cspA ( down-regulated ) negatively affect cell aggregation and/or surface attachment ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to fecR and cspA , the yoaD gene is activated by the CsgD protein ( Table 3 ) , although it also negatively affects cell aggregation ( Fig. 5A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Constitutive CsgD expression affects the transcription of a number of genes and represses the fecR and cspA regulatory genes , which play a negative role in bioﬁlm formation and cell-cell aggregation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data suggest that constitutive CsgD expression has a strong effect on the cold shock regulon ( Table 3 ) and that cspA , which encodes the major cold adaptation protein in E. coli , may be involved in the negative regulation of cell aggregation ( Fig. 5A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>W3110 reaches very similar S levels in stationary phase as MC4100 ( data not shown ) and also expresses the curli genes ( assayed using a single-copy csgB lacZ reporter fusion ) under the same control of S , MlrA , YdaM , YciR , and CsgD as MC4100 ( Supplemental Fig .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18765794" target="_blank">18765794</a>]<br></li>
<li>In parallel , we monitored the expression of the target of CsgD regulation , i.e. the csgBAC curli operon , by using a single copy csgB : : lacZ reporter fusion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>Role of the GGDEF/EAL proteins YdaM and YciR and growth temperature in the expression of CsgD and the csgBAC operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>During entry into stationary phase , sS is induced and exerts multiple activating effects in parallel ( on the expression of the GGDEF/EAL proteins YdaM/YciR and of the serially arranged activators MlrA and CsgD ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the curli control cascade , YhdA stimulates the expression of the GGDEF protein YdaM , but the finding that its effect on CsgD ( both on csgD mRNA and CsgD protein ; Figs 4 and 5 ) is stronger than its effect on YdaM expression suggests that it also plays a second , more direct role in csgD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19332833" target="_blank">19332833</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to further conﬁrm that YdaM and YciR are not involved in a post-transcriptional control of csgD expression or in CsgD activity , we eliminated the natural transcriptional control of csgD by expressing it ectopically under the control of the arabinose-inducible pBAD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>The failure to detect the inﬂuence of csgD knockout under steady-state growth in exponential phase may be due to the low-level expression of CsgD , as detected by Western blotting ( 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>Protein pattern analysis of E. coli cells in stationary phase shows that CsgD affects the expression of several proteins encoded by S-dependent genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>( C ) Conﬁrmation of CsgD expression in pBADcsgD-transformed E. coli BWcsgDF1D by Western blot analysis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , CsgD represses the transcription of DksA which , together with ppGpp , plays an important role in reorganizing gene expression in stationary phase , in particular by inducing the RpoS regulon ( 58 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides more efﬁcient expression of the csgDEFG operon , however , it is likely that CsgD - S interaction plays a more general role , i.e. , to coordinate the production of adhesion and cell aggregation factor ( curli ﬁbers and cellulose ) to S-depen-dent gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>The impact of CsgD on expression of genes not related to adhesion factors ' production , such as tnaA and anaerobic genes , as well as the rpoS regulon , is likely to reﬂect the cell 's need to reprogram its global gene expression in response to transition from planktonic cells to bioﬁlm .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Negative regulation of gene expression by CsgD can further stimulate adhesion and induce metabolic adaptation to growth as a bioﬁlm or as cell aggregates .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>The relative amounts of these products have not been determined , and it is possible the high level of expression reflects the need for large amounts of one or more of the other gene products rather than CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , CsgD expression also appears to affect expression of the tnaA gene ( Fig. 2A ) , whose product catalyzes tryptophan degradation to indole and pyruvate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , single genes that showed signiﬁcant induction but belonged to an operon in which no other gene was affected by CsgD expression were also discarded .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Maximal expression of csgDEFG was lower in strain MH968 lacking CsgD ( Figs. 2d , 3b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that , under some conditions , CsgD can regulate its own expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , expression of the hmp gene was higher in the cells lacking CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
<li>These observations show that ompR234-dependent expression of csgD and activation of the csgD-dependent operons take place at very different stages in cell growth , strongly suggesting that the CsgD protein might be activated post-transcriptionally in stationary phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>ompR234-independent CsgD expression resulted in activation of the csgB promoter , and in repression of pepD and yagS expression ( data not shown ) , strongly suggesting that these genes are indeed directly controlled by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 5 , CsgD can increase transcription levels of the iraP gene by 15-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , we also observed a reduced amount of the Dps protein in the outer membrane protein fraction of PHL565/pT7-CsgD ( Fig. 1 ) and a twofold reduction in dps transcription in the PHL565/pT7 ¬ CsgD strain ( data not shown ) , suggesting that there is possible negative control of the dps gene by CsgD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show here that CsgD positively controls S expression by activation of the iraP gene , a S protein stabilization factor ( 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>We report here that CsgD transcription activation of the iraP gene does indeed result in a signiﬁcant increase of S intracellular concentratio by positively affecting S protein stability ( Fig. 6 and 7 ) , thus leading to altered expression of S-dependent genes ( Fig. 2 , 3 , 4B , and 6B and Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of its own promoter by CsgD is suggested by increased production of the CsgG protein ( Fig. 2 ) , encoded by a gene which is part of the csgDEFG operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Either way , an increase in the cellular S pool in conditions permitting csg gene expression ( i.e. , low osmolarity ) leads to increased transcription from the csgD promoter ; in turn , production of the CsgD protein results in iraP activation and consequent further stabilization of S. Evidence for this auto-regulatory mechanism in the MG1655 strain is provided by S-dependent activation of the csgD promoter in the presence of pT7CsgD ( Fig. 4B ) and by consequent production of proteins encoded by the csgDEFG operon , such as CsgG ( Fig. 2C ) , in response to CsgD-dependent accumulation of S. Indeed , S-dependent activation of the csgDEFG operon observed in Fig. 4B is impaired in an iraP mutant strain ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to known members of the rpoS regulon , we ﬁnd that expression of the PﬂB protein ( band 1 ) , encoded by a gene thus far never described as S dependent , is stimulated by CsgD in the MG1655 background only , suggesting that its CsgD-depen-dent expression requires a functional rpoS gene ( Fig. 2A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Temperature-dependent regulation of curli - and cellulose-related genes Our results suggest that , despite constitutive expression of the CsgD protein in MG1655/pT7CsgD , cellulose biosynthesis does not take place at 37 uC , in contrast to curli production ( Fig. 1b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18599830" target="_blank">18599830</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD-induced iraP expression in either MG1655/pT7CsgD or PHL628 is consistent with increased production of proteins encoded by rpoS-dependent genes observed in both strains ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>CsgD modulation of the rpoS regulon ( or at least of a subset of S-dependent genes ) via iraP activation was observed both in MG1655 transformed with the pT7CsgD plasmid , allowing low-level , constitutive expression of the CsgD protein , and in the curli-proﬁcient PHL628 strain ( 53 ) , in which the csgD gene is expressed from its own promoter ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>We also found that CsgD activates the transcription of ihfB ( Fig. 6B ) itself known to activate csgD transcription in exponential phase ( 49 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272779" target="_blank">24272779</a>]<br></li>
<li>The molecular mechanisms of action of MlrA ( in csgD transcription ) and CsgD ( in csgBAC transcription ) have not been clariﬁed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17010156" target="_blank">17010156</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is possible that CsgD might repress yagS transcription by preventing elongation by RNA polymerase , rather than controlling the expression of a speciﬁc yagS promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523117" target="_blank">14523117</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , unlike curli-producing strains in which csgD expression is driven from its own promoter , the levels of csgD transcription in PHL565/pT7-CsgD do not vary signiﬁcantly in different growth conditions , again as determined by real-time PCR experiments ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased csgD transcription was exclusively due to the presence of the pT7-CsgD expression vector and was independent of the csgDEFG promoter , as indicated by a lack of any increase in csgEFG transcripts ( see the results for real-time PCR experiments ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Constitutive CsgD expression promotes bioﬁlm formation by PHL565 and activates transcription from the csgBAC promoter ; however , csgBAC expression remains dependent on temperature and the growth medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since CsgD expression from the pT7-CsgD plasmid was independent of the csgDEFG promoter , the observation that pT7-CsgD induced bioﬁlm formation by PHL565 more efﬁciently in M9Glu/sup than in LB strongly suggested that me-dium-dependent curli regulation takes place at a step after csgD transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike the levels of transcription of the csgBAC operon , the levels of transcription of the csgE , csgF and csgG genes ( i.e. , the csgDEFG operon ) were not altered by the presence of the pT7-CsgD plasmid , strongly suggesting that the CsgD protein does not regulate its own gene and indicating that , despite the presence of a functional chromosomal copy of csgD in the PHL565/pT7-CsgD strain , csgD expression is solely dependent on the plasmid copy of the gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Constitutive expression of the csgD gene from the pT7-CsgD plasmid results in a fully active CsgD protein that is able to promote surface colonization by PHL565 in a curli-dependent fashion ( Fig. 2 ) and to activate transcription at the csgBAC promoter ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16513732" target="_blank">16513732</a>]<br></li>
<li>Accordingly , expression of csgB that is under the positive control of CsgD was not detected ( Fig. 6 , csgB lane ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23233451" target="_blank">23233451</a>]<br></li>
<li>To overcome the masking effect by other transcription factors , CsgD was overexpressed by using an arabinose-inducible expression vector ( Fig. 8C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21421764" target="_blank">21421764</a>]<br></li>
<li>As ectopic expression of CsgD from exactly the same csgD mRNA transcribed from the pBAD promoter was not altered by the yegE and yhjH mutations ( Supplemental Fig .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18765794" target="_blank">18765794</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , higher levels of csgD transcription were detected in the exponential phase , earlier than the transcription from its target promoter csgBA , suggesting that CsgD might be subjected to posttranscriptional regulation and might possibly regulate its own expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11717281" target="_blank">11717281</a>]<br></li>
<li>S8 ) , we conclude that the YegE/YhjH system controls csgD transcription rather than csgD mRNA degradation , and by affecting CsgD levels , regulates curli expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18765794" target="_blank">18765794</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results shown in Fig. 4 indicate that CsgD expression results in increased transcription levels for both the csgB and the csgD promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17873038" target="_blank">17873038</a>]<br></li>
<li>When they increased CsgD levels by expressing it from a plasmid , expression of their csgD reporter increased .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23824318" target="_blank">23824318</a>]<br></li>
